echo '<h2>Arabs and Africa</h2>';
echo '<p>The Arab world\'s relationship with Africa is ancient, complex, and deeply consequential — encompassing trade, Islam, the trans-Saharan slave trade, colonization of North and East Africa, and contemporary political and economic relations. For the Igbo specifically, the Arab connection operates through Islam (which reached northern Nigeria via trans-Saharan trade routes from the 11th century onward), through the political structure of Nigeria (where northern Nigeria\'s Muslim Hausa-Fulani elite has been the dominant force in federal politics), and through global oil markets that connect Nigerian crude to Gulf Arab investment.</p>';
echo '<h2>The Trans-Saharan Slave Trade</h2>';
echo '<p>Long before the Atlantic slave trade, Arab merchants conducted a trans-Saharan and East African slave trade that transported millions of Africans to North Africa, the Middle East, and the Persian Gulf. Estimates suggest that between 650 CE and 1900 CE, approximately 17 million Africans were enslaved through the trans-Saharan, Red Sea, and Indian Ocean routes. Unlike the Atlantic slave trade, which generated detailed records through European commercial bureaucracy, the Arab slave trade is less well-documented — partly because it continued longer and ended more gradually, and partly because fewer scholars have focused on it.</p>';
echo '<h2>Islam and Northern Nigeria</h2>';
echo '<p>Islam reached the Hausa states of northern Nigeria via trans-Saharan trade routes around the 11th century CE. The Sokoto Jihad of 1804–1808, led by Usman dan Fodio, established the Sokoto Caliphate — the largest state in Africa at the time — and consolidated Islamic authority across northern Nigeria. The Sokoto Caliphate\'s structures were largely preserved by British indirect rule and continue to shape northern Nigerian politics today. The Hausa-Fulani Islamic north and the predominantly Christian Igbo southeast represent the most significant political and cultural fault line in Nigeria.</p>';
